        {
          "type": "text",
          "name": "help_text",
          "value": "These are tasks that invite playing around. Some are EFM puzzles, which are covered elsewhere. They are also questions and puzzles that are not narrowly focused and do not necessarily have a small set of answers The point is to invite exploration and play, and then for students to look for interesting new places to take the inquiry to.\n\nPeter Liljedahl's book Mathematics Tasks for the Thinking Classroom for K-3 has 50 tasks with detailed suggestions for each one. I bet we could make use of quite a few of them (with proper recognition).\n\nSome of these will be ideas from Mike F's Open-Ended Math Tasks notebook. Here are some ideas from his notebook. This can of course be expanded with ideas from other sources. Each of these that we decide to use will need a full discussion. Perhaps some of the more interesting What do you Notice and What do you Wonder tasks could go in here?\n\n**Shapes and Properties**\n* Which of These is Not Like the Others\n* Some of the EFM puzzles about shapes and multiple pieces\n\n**Counting**\n* Dot Talks\n* EFM puzzles for consecutive numbers\n\n**Adding and Subtracting**\nThese are brief descriptions put in an accordion format. Each one will have a much longer description with ideas for how to teach them.",
